{"title_page": "Sahib Jamal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| consort   = yes\n| name      = Sahib Jamal\n| image     = Anarkali tomb, November 2008.jpg\n| caption   = The tomb of Sahib Jamal in Lahore\n| title     = [[Begum|Begum-i-Padishah]]<br>\u0628\u06cc\u06af\u0645 \u067e\u0627\u062f\u0634\u0627\u0647\n| reign     =\n| spouse    = [[Jahangir]] (pre-accession)\n| issue     = [[Parviz (Mughal prince)|Sultan Parviz Mirza]]\n| house     = [[Timurid dynasty|Timurid]] ''(by marriage)''\n| father    = Khwaja Hasan\n| mother    =\n| birth_date      =\n| birth_place     = [[Herat]], [[Afghanistan]]\n| death_date      = {{circa}} 25 June 1599<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Thackston |editor-first=Wheeler M. |translator=Thackston |title=The Jahangirnama : memoirs of Jahangir, Emperor of India|url=https://archive.org/details/jahangirnamamemo00jaha|date=1999|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=New York [u.a.]|isbn=9780195127188|page=[https://archive.org/details/jahangirnamamemo00jaha/page/8 8]}}</ref>\n| death_place     = [[Lahore]], [[Pakistan]]\n| place of burial = [[Tomb of Anarkali|Tomb of Sahib Jamal]], Lahore\n| religion        = [[Islam]]\n| full name       = '''Persian'''<br>'''_______''<br>''''\u0635\u0627\u062d\u0628 \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0644'''\n}}\n\n'''Sahib Jamal''' ({{lang-fa|\u0635\u0627\u062d\u0628 \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0644}}; died {{circa}} 25 June 1599) was the third wife of Prince Salim Mirza, the future Mughal emperor [[Jahangir]]. She was the mother of Salim's second son, Prince [[Parviz (Mughal prince)|Parviz]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Balabanlilar|first=Lisa|title=Imperial Identity in the Mughal Empire : Memory and Dynastic Politics in Early Modern South and Central Asia|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781848857261|page=10|year=2012}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nSahib Jamal was of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shujauddin|first1=Mohammad|last2=Shujauddin|first2=Razia|title=The Life and Times of Noor Jahan|date=1967|publisher=The Caravan Book House|location=Lahore|language=en|page=71}}</ref> and was the daughter of a respected [[Muslim]] religious personality, Khwaja Hasan of [[Herat]], making her the cousin of [[Zain Khan Koka]], who was a leading official in the [[Mugal Empire]] under [[Akbar]], including serving for a time as governor of [[Kabul]].<ref name=Findly>{{cite book|last1=Findly|first1=Ellison Banks|title=Nur Jahan: Empress of Mughal India|date=1993|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195360608|pages=124 125}}</ref> Her father, Khwaja Hasan, was known widely for his scholarship and studies in the techniques of warfare. Akbar held him in high esteem, and often discussed with him the spiritual problems that often agitated his mind.<ref name=\"Lal\" /> Zain Khan's daughter, [[Khas Mahal]] was also married to Jahangir.<ref>{{cite book|first=Ziyaud-Din A.|last=Desai|title=Pur\u0101-prak\u0101\u015ba: Recent Researches in Epigraphy, Numismatics, Manuscriptology, Persian Literature, Art, Architecture, Archaeology, History and Conservation: Dr. Z.A. Desai Commemoration Volume, Volume 1\n|publisher=Bharatiya Kala Prakashan|year=2003|pages=281|isbn=978-8-180-90007-5}}</ref>\n\nSahib Jamal was a beautiful,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lal|first1=K.S.|title=The Mughal harem|date=1988|publisher=Aditya Prakashan|location=New Delhi|isbn=9788185179032|page=27}}</ref> highly cultured and well educated woman, who was fully conversant with the rules and etiquettes of the palace.<ref name=Lal>{{cite book|last1=Lal|first1=Muni|title=Jahangir|date=1983|publisher=Vikas|location=New Delhi|isbn=9780706922714|pages=27 28}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nSalim had fallen in love with her and they got married in October 1589,<ref>{{cite book|first1=Sh\u0101hnav\u0101z Kh\u0101n|last1=Awang\u0101b\u0101d\u012b|first2=Baini|last2=Prasad|first3='Abd al-Hayy ibn|last3=Sh\u0101hnav\u0101z|title=The Ma\u0101thir-ul-umar\u0101: Being biographies of the Mu\u1e25ammadan and Hindu officers of the Timurid sovereigns of India from 1500 to about 1780 A.D.|publisher=Janaki Prakashan|year=1979|pages=1023|isbn=}}</ref> in a lavish and grand marriage ceremony. Upon her marriage, she was given the title \"Sahib Jamal\", which literally means (\"Paragon of Beauty\") or (\"Mistress of Beauty\") which was chosen by Akbar himself, by which name she came to be styled thereafter.<ref>{{cite book|last=Prasad|first=Beni|title=History of Jahangir|year=1940|publisher=Indian Press, Limited|page=26|editor=3}}</ref>\n\nSahib Jamal bore her husband two children: his second son, [[Muhammad Parviz|Sultan Parviz Mirza]], as well as a daughter, who died in infancy.<ref name=Lal/>\n\nIn 1596 Salim became violently enamoured of Khas Mahal, the daughter of Zain Khan, and meditated marrying her. Akbar was displeased at the impropriety. The cause of Akbar's objection was Sahib Jamal who had already been married to Salim. Akbar objected to marriages between near relations. However, when Akbar saw that Salim's heart was immoderately affected, he, of necessity, gave his consent.<ref name name=\"henry\">{{cite book|title=Akbarnama of Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak - Volume III|first=Henry|last=Beveridge|year=1907|publisher=Asiatic Society, Calcutta|pages=1058\u20139 n. 3|isbn=}}</ref>\n\n==Death and burial place==\nSahib Jamal died {{circa}} 25 June 1599 in [[Lahore]], present-day [[Pakistan]], and was also buried there. Construction of her tomb dates to either 1599 [[Common era|C.E.]] or 1615 C.E.<ref name=Anarkali>{{cite news|title=Legend: Anarkali: myth, mystery and history|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/694833/legend-anarkali-myth-mystery-and-history|accessdate=23 August 2016|agency=Dawn|date=11 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThere is a popular misconception that the [[Tomb of Anarkali|Tomb of Sahib Jamal]] in Lahore is the tomb of the legendary dancing girl [[Anarkali]]. As per the legend, the tomb was said to be built by the Mughal emperor Jahangir for his love Anarkali, who was caught by Emperor Akbar for exchanging glances with Jahangir, at the time known as Prince Salim. Anarkali was reportedly a concubine of Akbar, and this action reportedly enraged Akbar so much, that he had Anarkali interred alive in a wall. When Prince Salim ascended the throne and took the name \"Jahangir,\" he is reported to have ordered the construction of a tomb over the site of the wall in which Anarkali was reportedly buried.<ref name=Anarkali/>\n\n18th century historian Abdullah Chagatai reported that the tomb was not the resting place for Anarkali, but instead for Jahangir's beloved wife Sahib Jamal.<ref name=Anarkali/> Many modern historians accept the credulity of this account.<ref name=\"Anarkali's Tomb\">{{cite web|title=Anarkali's Tomb|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/tomb_anarkali.html|website=Lahore Sites|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref> The building is currently used as the Punjab Archives, so access to the public is limited.\n\n[[File:Anarkali tomb sarcophagus, November 2008.jpg|thumb|The richly carved cenotaph is made of white [[marble]].]]\nSahib Jamal's white marble cenotaph features carvings with the [[Names of God in Islam|99 names of Allah]], and was described by 19th century historians as \"one of the finest pieces of carving in the world.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eastwick|first1=Edward Backhouse|title=Handbook of the Punjab, Western Rajputana, Kashmir, and Upper Sindh|date=1883|publisher=John Murray, Albemarle Street|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the 99 names of Allah, the cenotaph is inscribed with a Persian couplet written by the Emperor Jahangir which reads: \"Ah! could I behold the face of my beloved once more, I would give thanks unto my God until the day of resurrection.\"<ref name=\"Anarkali's Tomb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sahib Jamal}}\n[[Category:1599 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian female royalty]]\n[[Category:Mughal nobility]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Women of the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:Indian queen consorts]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:16th-century Indian women]]\n[[Category:Indian people of Turkish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| consort   = yes\n| name      = Sahib Jamal\n| image     = Anarkali tomb, November 2008.jpg\n| caption   = The tomb of Sahib Jamal in Lahore\n| title     = [[Begum|Begum-i-Padishah]]<br>\u0628\u06cc\u06af\u0645 \u067e\u0627\u062f\u0634\u0627\u0647\n| reign     =\n| spouse    = [[Jahangir]] (pre-accession)\n| issue     = [[Parviz (Mughal prince)|Sultan Parviz Mirza]]\n| house     = [[Timurid dynasty|Timurid]] ''(by marriage)''\n| father    = Khwaja Hasan\n| mother    =\n| birth_date      =\n| birth_place     = [[Herat]], [[Afghanistan]]\n| death_date      = {{circa}} 25 June 1599<ref>{{cite book|last1=transl.|last2=ed.|last3=Thackston|first3=annot. by Wheeler M.|title=The Jahangirnama : memoirs of Jahangir, Emperor of India|url=https://archive.org/details/jahangirnamamemo00jaha|date=1999|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=New York [u.a.]|isbn=9780195127188|page=[https://archive.org/details/jahangirnamamemo00jaha/page/8 8]}}</ref>\n| death_place     = [[Lahore]], [[Pakistan]]\n| place of burial = [[Tomb of Anarkali|Tomb of Sahib Jamal]], Lahore\n| religion        = [[Islam]]\n| full name       = '''Persian'''<br>'''_______''<br>''''\u0635\u0627\u062d\u0628 \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0644'''\n}}\n\n'''Sahib Jamal''' ({{lang-fa|\u0635\u0627\u062d\u0628 \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0644}}; died {{circa}} 25 June 1599) was the third wife of Prince Salim Mirza, the future Mughal emperor [[Jahangir]]. She was the mother of Salim's second son, Prince [[Parviz (Mughal prince)|Parviz]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Balabanlilar|first=Lisa|title=Imperial Identity in the Mughal Empire : Memory and Dynastic Politics in Early Modern South and Central Asia|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781848857261|page=10|year=2012}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nSahib Jamal was of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shujauddin|first1=Mohammad|last2=Shujauddin|first2=Razia|title=The Life and Times of Noor Jahan|date=1967|publisher=The Caravan Book House|location=Lahore|language=en|page=71}}</ref> and was the daughter of a respected [[Muslim]] religious personality, Khwaja Hasan of [[Herat]], making her the cousin of [[Zain Khan Koka]], who was a leading official in the [[Mugal Empire]] under [[Akbar]], including serving for a time as governor of [[Kabul]].<ref name=Findly>{{cite book|last1=Findly|first1=Ellison Banks|title=Nur Jahan: Empress of Mughal India|date=1993|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195360608|pages=124 125}}</ref> Her father, Khwaja Hasan, was known widely for his scholarship and studies in the techniques of warfare. Akbar held him in high esteem, and often discussed with him the spiritual problems that often agitated his mind.<ref name=\"Lal\" /> Zain Khan's daughter, [[Khas Mahal]] was also married to Jahangir.<ref>{{cite book|first=Ziyaud-Din A.|last=Desai|title=Pur\u0101-prak\u0101\u015ba: Recent Researches in Epigraphy, Numismatics, Manuscriptology, Persian Literature, Art, Architecture, Archaeology, History and Conservation: Dr. Z.A. Desai Commemoration Volume, Volume 1\n|publisher=Bharatiya Kala Prakashan|year=2003|pages=281|isbn=978-8-180-90007-5}}</ref>\n\nSahib Jamal was a beautiful,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lal|first1=K.S.|title=The Mughal harem|date=1988|publisher=Aditya Prakashan|location=New Delhi|isbn=9788185179032|page=27}}</ref> highly cultured and well educated woman, who was fully conversant with the rules and etiquettes of the palace.<ref name=Lal>{{cite book|last1=Lal|first1=Muni|title=Jahangir|date=1983|publisher=Vikas|location=New Delhi|isbn=9780706922714|pages=27 28}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\nSalim had fallen in love with her and they got married in October 1589,<ref>{{cite book|first1=Sh\u0101hnav\u0101z Kh\u0101n|last1=Awang\u0101b\u0101d\u012b|first2=Baini|last2=Prasad|first3='Abd al-Hayy ibn|last3=Sh\u0101hnav\u0101z|title=The Ma\u0101thir-ul-umar\u0101: Being biographies of the Mu\u1e25ammadan and Hindu officers of the Timurid sovereigns of India from 1500 to about 1780 A.D.|publisher=Janaki Prakashan|year=1979|pages=1023|isbn=}}</ref> in a lavish and grand marriage ceremony. Upon her marriage, she was given the title \"Sahib Jamal\", which literally means (\"Paragon of Beauty\") or (\"Mistress of Beauty\") which was chosen by Akbar himself, by which name she came to be styled thereafter.<ref>{{cite book|last=Prasad|first=Beni|title=History of Jahangir|year=1940|publisher=Indian Press, Limited|page=26|editor=3}}</ref>\n\nSahib Jamal bore her husband two children: his second son, [[Muhammad Parviz|Sultan Parviz Mirza]], as well as a daughter, who died in infancy.<ref name=Lal/>\n\nIn 1596 Salim became violently enamoured of Khas Mahal, the daughter of Zain Khan, and meditated marrying her. Akbar was displeased at the impropriety. The cause of Akbar's objection was Sahib Jamal who had already been married to Salim. Akbar objected to marriages between near relations. However, when Akbar saw that Salim's heart was immoderately affected, he, of necessity, gave his consent.<ref name name=\"henry\">{{cite book|title=Akbarnama of Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak - Volume III|first=Henry|last=Beveridge|year=1907|publisher=Asiatic Society, Calcutta|pages=1058\u20139 n. 3|isbn=}}</ref>\n\n==Death and burial place==\nSahib Jamal died {{circa}} 25 June 1599 in [[Lahore]], present-day [[Pakistan]], and was also buried there. Construction of her tomb dates to either 1599 [[Common era|C.E.]] or 1615 C.E.<ref name=Anarkali>{{cite news|title=Legend: Anarkali: myth, mystery and history|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/694833/legend-anarkali-myth-mystery-and-history|accessdate=23 August 2016|agency=Dawn|date=11 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThere is a popular misconception that the [[Tomb of Anarkali|Tomb of Sahib Jamal]] in Lahore is the tomb of the legendary dancing girl [[Anarkali]]. As per the legend, the tomb was said to be built by the Mughal emperor Jahangir for his love Anarkali, who was caught by Emperor Akbar for exchanging glances with Jahangir, at the time known as Prince Salim. Anarkali was reportedly a concubine of Akbar, and this action reportedly enraged Akbar so much, that he had Anarkali interred alive in a wall. When Prince Salim ascended the throne and took the name \"Jahangir,\" he is reported to have ordered the construction of a tomb over the site of the wall in which Anarkali was reportedly buried.<ref name=Anarkali/>\n\n18th century historian Abdullah Chagatai reported that the tomb was not the resting place for Anarkali, but instead for Jahangir's beloved wife Sahib Jamal.<ref name=Anarkali/> Many modern historians accept the credulity of this account.<ref name=\"Anarkali's Tomb\">{{cite web|title=Anarkali's Tomb|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/tomb_anarkali.html|website=Lahore Sites|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref> The building is currently used as the Punjab Archives, so access to the public is limited.\n\n[[File:Anarkali tomb sarcophagus, November 2008.jpg|thumb|The richly carved cenotaph is made of white [[marble]].]]\nSahib Jamal's white marble cenotaph features carvings with the [[Names of God in Islam|99 names of Allah]], and was described by 19th century historians as \"one of the finest pieces of carving in the world.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eastwick|first1=Edward Backhouse|title=Handbook of the Punjab, Western Rajputana, Kashmir, and Upper Sindh|date=1883|publisher=John Murray, Albemarle Street|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the 99 names of Allah, the cenotaph is inscribed with a Persian couplet written by the Emperor Jahangir which reads: \"Ah! could I behold the face of my beloved once more, I would give thanks unto my God until the day of resurrection.\"<ref name=\"Anarkali's Tomb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFA